<subSubSection id="95C38AF3FFA9C439FF4EFE4EFA92C0C3" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFA9C439FF4EFE4EFBFBC076" blockId="1.[136,1452,460,775]" box="[189,1052,496,523]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FF4EFE4EFEA2C076" bold="true" box="[189,325,496,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Etymology:</emphasis>
—the name refers to the region where the specimen was collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFA9C439FF7BFDAAFA92C0C3" blockId="1.[136,1452,460,775]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">
Basidioma annual, resupinate; pore surface salmon (45) to peach (46) colored when fresh and snuff brown (17) when dry, fading to yellowish brown, pores shallow, angular to honeycomb in a reticulate pattern, 1−3 per mm, margin narrow, concolorous with pore surface, tube layer up to 
<quantity id="1A21749DFFA9C439FD53FDE2FD12C00B" box="[672,757,604,631]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
deep, drying brittle, subiculum thin, up to 300 μm thick, soft, white. Hyphal system monomitic, generative hyphae simple-septate, thin-walled, 2−5 μm in diam. Cystidia or other sterile hymenial elements absent. Basidia not seen. Basidiospores ellipsoid, 3 × 2 μm, negative in Melzer’s reagent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95C38AF3FFA9C439FF4EFD76FBF8C09E" box="[189,1055,712,739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFA9C439FF4EFD76FBF8C09E" blockId="1.[136,1452,460,775]" box="[189,1055,712,739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FF4EFD76FEBEC09E" bold="true" box="[189,345,712,738]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Distribution:</emphasis>
—Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="026267DAFFA9C439FD9DFD77FD79C09F" box="[622,670,713,739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">type</typeStatus>
locality in state of 
<collectingRegion id="1F1D179AFFA9C439FC87FD76FC2FC09E" box="[884,968,712,738]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Amapá</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A5CE99E8FFA9C439FC20FD76FBFCC09E" box="[979,1051,712,738]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95C38AF3FFA9C43AFF4EFD52FC9DC3EC" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="178" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFA9C439FF4EFD52FD67C17A" blockId="1.[136,1452,460,775]" box="[189,640,748,775]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FF4EFD52FEC1C17A" bold="true" box="[189,294,748,774]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Ecology:</emphasis>
—On a dead, fallen hardwood.
</paragraph>
<caption id="89A689F0FFA9C439FF7BF81FFE22C5A7" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5143891" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5143891" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5143891/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" startId="1.[136,229,1953,1975]" targetBox="[151,1436,818,1925]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFA9C439FF7BF81FFE22C5A7" blockId="1.[136,1452,1953,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FF7BF81FFF1FC5CA" bold="true" box="[136,248,1953,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">FIGURE 1</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="1AD9A2FBFFA9C439FEF6F81FFDC9C5CB" authority="A. Dried" authorityName="A. Dried" box="[261,558,1953,1975]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Ceriporia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="1" pageNumber="177" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FEF6F81FFE35C5CB" box="[261,466,1953,1975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">Ceriporia amazonica</emphasis>
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FE2AF81FFE0DC5CA" bold="true" box="[473,490,1953,1974]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">A</emphasis>
. Dried
</taxonomicName>
basidiomata; 
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FD46F81FFD22C5CA" bold="true" box="[693,709,1953,1974]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">B</emphasis>
. Fresh basidiomata; 
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFA9C439FC7CF81FFC40C5CB" bold="true" box="[911,935,1953,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="177">C.</emphasis>
Basidiospores on the left; Pores on the right. Photos: H. Sotão; drawings L. Ryvarden.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="DD66D978FFAAC43AFF4EFF20FC9DC3EC" blockId="2.[136,1451,158,401]" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFF4EFF20FE36C2C4" bold="true" box="[189,465,158,184]" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">Taxonomic remarks:—</emphasis>
The salmon-coloured basidioma makes this a conspicuous species when observed in the field. 
<taxonomicName id="1AD9A2FBFFAAC43AFF39FF7DFD22C2A0" authority="(Schwein. ex Fr.) Rajchenb." authorityName="Rajchenb." baseAuthorityName="Fr." box="[202,709,194,221]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Ceriporia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="spissa">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFF39FF7DFE64C2A0" box="[202,387,195,221]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">Ceriporia spissa</emphasis>
(Schwein. ex Fr.) Rajchenb.
</taxonomicName>
has a similar color, but it has pores ranging from 7−9 per mm and allantoid basidiospores (
<bibRefCitation id="B948A489FFAAC43AFE66FF58FDB3C37C" author="Aime, L. &amp; Ryvarden, L. &amp; Henkel, T. W." box="[405,596,230,256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" pagination="15 - 31" refId="ref2551" refString="Aime, L., Ryvarden, L. &amp; Henkel, T. W. (2007) Studies in Neotropical polypores 22. Additional new and rare species from Guyana. Synopsis Fungorum 23: 15 - 31." type="journal article" year="2007">
Aime 
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFE28FF59FDF5C37C" box="[475,530,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, the basidiospores of 
<taxonomicName id="1AD9A2FBFFAAC43AFC3EFF59FB82C37C" box="[973,1125,231,257]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Ceriporia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFC3EFF59FB82C37C" box="[973,1125,231,257]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">C. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are among the smallest in the genus and should aid in the identification of the species. 
<taxonomicName id="1AD9A2FBFFAAC43AFD0FFEB5FB30C358" authority="M. Mata &amp; Ryvarden" authorityName="M. Mata &amp; Ryvarden" box="[764,1239,266,293]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Ceriporia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="incrustata">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFD0FFEB5FC04C358" box="[764,995,267,293]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">Ceriporia incrustata</emphasis>
M. Mata &amp; Ryvarden
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1AD9A2FBFFAAC43AFAF8FEB5FE7FC334" authority="I. Lindblad &amp; Ryvarden" authorityName="I. Lindblad &amp; Ryvarden" authorityYear="1999" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Ceriporia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="microspora">
<emphasis id="EFAD056AFFAAC43AFAF8FEB5FA4CC358" box="[1291,1451,267,293]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="178">C. microspora</emphasis>
I. Lindblad &amp; Ryvarden
</taxonomicName>
have basidiospores of similar size (3−3.5 × 1.8−2 μm and 3−3.5 × 1.5−2 μm, respectively), but smaller pores (6−8 per mm in both species). Besides, the former has ochraceous basidiomata and the latter, white basidiomata (
<bibRefCitation id="B948A489FFAAC43AFEEDFEC8FDB1C3EC" author="Lindblad, I. &amp; Ryvarden, L." box="[286,598,374,400]" pageId="2" pageNumber="178" pagination="335 - 359" refId="ref2921" refString="Lindblad, I. &amp; Ryvarden, L. (1999) Studies in neotropical polypores. 3. New and interesting Basidiomycetes (Poriales) from Costa Rica. Mycotaxon 71: 335 - 359." type="journal article" year="1999">Lindblad &amp; Ryvarden 1999</bibRefCitation>
, Mata &amp; Ryvarden 2010).
</paragraph>
